1
00:00:12,595 --> 00:00:14,597
Three weeks earlier.

2
00:00:15,265 --> 00:00:16,850
Huh?

3
00:00:17,183 --> 00:00:20,937
Sometimes a movie or show begins on
a random scene with no context,

4
00:00:21,146 --> 00:00:24,023
encouraging you to wonder,
"Whoa. How'd this scenario come to be?"

5
00:00:24,232 --> 00:00:27,193
Then it cuts to black and a title comes up
saying "three weeks earlier"?

6
00:00:27,318 --> 00:00:28,361
Uh-huh.

7
00:00:28,528 --> 00:00:30,780
Here we are, sitting in silence,
crammed into an RV,

8
00:00:30,989 --> 00:00:32,949
winding through
the roads of Colorado,

9
00:00:33,158 --> 00:00:35,618
with a 19-foot
fiberglass hand tied to the roof.

10
00:00:37,829 --> 00:00:41,124
If there was a time to cut to
"three weeks earlier," it would be now.

11
00:00:43,084 --> 00:00:44,377
You know what I mean?

12
00:00:44,544 --> 00:00:46,421
[JEFF CLEARING THROAT]

13
00:00:49,215 --> 00:00:50,884
[GROANS]

14
00:00:53,303 --> 00:00:55,305
JEFF:
Elroy, you got any booze?

15
00:00:56,097 --> 00:00:57,557
Don't go through my stuff.

16
00:00:57,766 --> 00:01:00,602
This isn't a bus. You're standing in my
living room, kitchen and bedroom.

17
00:01:00,810 --> 00:01:06,274
Ooh. I never thought about that.
And your backyard is 24,900 miles long.

18
00:01:06,483 --> 00:01:09,527
Because it's the
circumference of the Earth.

19
00:01:09,736 --> 00:01:12,447
Because you have no home.

20
00:01:12,655 --> 00:01:14,657
Anyone need water?
What should we talk about?

21
00:01:14,741 --> 00:01:17,243
To make it intriguing,
someone should be injured

22
00:01:17,452 --> 00:01:20,872
in a way that makes you wonder.
Like if Britta had a black eye.

23
00:01:22,082 --> 00:01:24,459
Dean, can I speak to you privately?

24
00:01:24,667 --> 00:01:26,711
I'm pretty sure the answer is no.

25
00:01:26,920 --> 00:01:28,546
PELTON:
I'm coming up.

26
00:01:33,718 --> 00:01:37,180
You know, when I agreed to haul this thing
for you and the school,

27
00:01:37,388 --> 00:01:39,891
you didn't say anything about
six people back there.

28
00:01:40,099 --> 00:01:42,143
JEFF:
Man, I wonder what they're talking about.

29
00:01:42,352 --> 00:01:46,940
ANNIE: God, who knows.
They're sealed off behind this sound-proof vinyl.

30
00:01:47,148 --> 00:01:48,942
I will drive my house off a cliff!

31
00:01:49,025 --> 00:01:51,653
Elroy, we're not here to snoop or judge you.

32
00:01:51,861 --> 00:01:55,824
You're not the first person to
have dirty dishes, CD-ROM porn,

33
00:01:56,032 --> 00:02:00,245
and framed photos of yourself
with two biracial teenagers in a park.

34
00:02:00,453 --> 00:02:02,080
It's not that.

35
00:02:02,288 --> 00:02:03,915
All this weight.

36
00:02:04,124 --> 00:02:05,875
I may have...

37
00:02:06,084 --> 00:02:08,628
miscalculated the mileage.

38
00:02:10,004 --> 00:02:11,381
{\an8}[KNOCKING]

39
00:02:11,464 --> 00:02:13,550
JEFF:
Darn it. I want to hijack this RV,

40
00:02:13,758 --> 00:02:17,095
but I'm foiled by its impenetrable
post-2001 security measures.

41
00:02:17,303 --> 00:02:20,932
You keep driving and nobody else
needs to know about this. Understand?

42
00:02:21,141 --> 00:02:23,309
The last thing we need is a panic.

43
00:02:24,602 --> 00:02:26,229
What's going on? Are we out of gas?

44
00:02:26,437 --> 00:02:29,315
Yes! It's on empty! It's on empty!

45
00:02:29,524 --> 00:02:32,110
Never seen anything like it.
The needle is invisible.

46
00:02:32,318 --> 00:02:34,821
-Oh, my God
-There's no needle! It's gone!

47
00:02:35,029 --> 00:02:38,366
It's underneath the plastic or maybe
the engine tried to use it as fuel.

48
00:02:38,575 --> 00:02:40,618
-Stop yelling!
-Well, stop being out of gas.

49
00:02:40,827 --> 00:02:42,996
-You're freaking me out.
-You should freak out.

50
00:02:43,204 --> 00:02:48,418
I have been driving for 25 years and
I have never seen so little gas in my life.

51
00:02:48,501 --> 00:02:50,003
ALL: Aah!
-Stop, stop!

52
00:02:50,211 --> 00:02:53,339
I'm yelling even louder,
so you have to stop!

53
00:02:53,548 --> 00:02:56,509
We're not in control of the gas, okay?

54
00:02:56,718 --> 00:02:59,304
We have to focus on
what we can control.

55
00:02:59,512 --> 00:03:01,306
Is everyone's phone charged?

56
00:03:01,514 --> 00:03:04,350
JEFF: Yes. Charge your phones.
PELTON: Good idea. Smart thinking.

57
00:03:04,559 --> 00:03:06,352
-Okay.
JEFF: Okay.

58
00:03:06,477 --> 00:03:09,439
See?
We turned panic into preparedness.

59
00:03:09,856 --> 00:03:14,402
Now, if we do run out of gas,
guess who's got fully charged phones.

60
00:03:14,611 --> 00:03:17,071
ANNIE: Well-charged.
ABED: Full battery.

61
00:03:17,280 --> 00:03:19,449
For the love of God,
stop charging your phones!

62
00:03:20,950 --> 00:03:22,952
[ANNIE SCREAMS]

63
00:03:23,161 --> 00:03:26,456
[TIRES SCREECHING]

64
00:03:32,003 --> 00:03:34,047
Excuse me a moment.

65
00:03:35,965 --> 00:03:37,508
-What happened?
-I'm not telling you!

66
00:03:37,592 --> 00:03:40,386
-Fair enough. We're all gonna die.
ALL: Aah!

67
00:03:40,470 --> 00:03:42,180
[THE 88'S "AT LEAST IT WAS HERE" PLAYING]

68
00:03:42,263 --> 00:03:44,265
{\an8}<i>♪ Give me some rope</i>
<i>Tie me to dream ♪</i>

69
00:03:44,432 --> 00:03:47,477
{\an8}<i>♪ Give me the hope</i>
<i>To run out of steam ♪</i>

70
00:03:47,644 --> 00:03:51,064
{\an8}<i>♪ Somebody said</i>
<i>It can be here ♪</i>

71
00:03:51,147 --> 00:03:54,901
{\an8}<i>♪ We could be roped up, tied up</i>
<i>Dead in a year ♪</i>

72
00:03:55,068 --> 00:03:59,572
{\an8}<i>♪ I can't count the reasons</i>
<i>I should stay ♪</i>

73
00:04:00,281 --> 00:04:04,452
<i>♪ One by one</i>
<i>They all just fade away ♪♪</i>

74
00:04:12,418 --> 00:04:14,212
All in favor?

75
00:04:14,420 --> 00:04:16,714
{\an8}And that solves the matter
of the giant hand.

76
00:04:16,923 --> 00:04:18,466
-If there's no other business--
-Yes.

77
00:04:18,549 --> 00:04:21,219
{\an8}I'd like to establish this
as the opening for a flashback.

78
00:04:21,427 --> 00:04:22,679
No. Meeting adjourned.

79
00:04:25,390 --> 00:04:27,767
[ENGINE SPUTTERING]

80
00:04:31,729 --> 00:04:33,815
{\an8}Oh. So we're not doing the
"three weeks earlier" thing.

81
00:04:33,898 --> 00:04:37,360
{\an8}Abed, insert dialogue here about you
dropping the fourth-wall shtick.

82
00:04:37,568 --> 00:04:39,570
{\an8}-Nice.
-Careful you don't flood it.

83
00:04:39,779 --> 00:04:41,906
{\an8}That's the fifth time
you've reminded me.

84
00:04:42,115 --> 00:04:44,033
Sorry, it doesn't apply to our situation.

85
00:04:44,242 --> 00:04:45,952
I'm going to check the battery.

86
00:04:46,160 --> 00:04:48,538
Can you send someone or not?

87
00:04:48,746 --> 00:04:51,708
WOMAN: <i>Can you please hold?</i>
-No, I can't hold.

88
00:04:51,916 --> 00:04:53,001
Darn it.

89
00:04:53,209 --> 00:04:57,255
When they put you on hold,
you hang up and you call right back.

90
00:04:57,463 --> 00:05:00,008
-Frankie taught me that.
-Hi, it's me.

91
00:05:00,216 --> 00:05:02,927
Yeah, the one you put on hold.
See where that got you?

92
00:05:03,136 --> 00:05:04,804
-Can you send someone?
WOMAN: <i>Please hold.</i>

93
00:05:05,013 --> 00:05:06,347
FRANKIE:
Don't you dare.

94
00:05:06,556 --> 00:05:09,434
When they put you on hold,
hang up and call right back.

95
00:05:09,642 --> 00:05:13,396
{\an8}I can play this game all day.
I told you we need roadside service--

96
00:05:13,604 --> 00:05:16,399
{\an8}WOMAN: <i>Can you please hold?</i>
-Oh, you can't be serious.

97
00:05:16,607 --> 00:05:18,568
Well, hello. Guess who.

98
00:05:18,776 --> 00:05:23,740
{\an8}I got nothing but fingers and time, pal.
Roadside service, Moffit Pass.

99
00:05:23,823 --> 00:05:24,991
{\an8}[WOMAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

100
00:05:25,074 --> 00:05:27,160
{\an8}Well, you could have
told me that an hour ago.

101
00:05:28,328 --> 00:05:31,289
{\an8}Your RV is full of crazy ladies.
Goodbye.

102
00:05:32,582 --> 00:05:35,001
{\an8}Have any of you
heard of Armed Forces Day?

103
00:05:35,209 --> 00:05:37,503
{\an8}Apparently it's today
and it's really boning us.

104
00:05:37,712 --> 00:05:38,838
Yeah, here it is.

105
00:05:39,047 --> 00:05:40,840
Armed Forces Day, huh.

106
00:05:41,049 --> 00:05:42,759
Why would they put it in May?

107
00:05:42,967 --> 00:05:46,596
It's just sitting there in Memorial Day's shadow
like a military Hanukkah.

108
00:05:46,804 --> 00:05:50,391
Fitting that both war holidays have to fight
each other over the same month.

109
00:05:50,475 --> 00:05:53,144
Notable that the one we remember
is the one with the theme of memory.

110
00:05:53,352 --> 00:05:55,772
Way to make this about
justifying your sensibility.

111
00:05:55,980 --> 00:06:00,860
Well, apparently, Armed Forces Day
is the big one for tow truck drivers.

112
00:06:01,069 --> 00:06:05,531
There are three within 200 miles of this spot,
and they're all in the same parade.

113
00:06:05,740 --> 00:06:07,825
Maybe it'll come by this way,

114
00:06:08,034 --> 00:06:10,995
if we offer them instruments?

115
00:06:11,204 --> 00:06:14,123
JEFF: Nobody reroutes parades.
-They rerouted Kennedy's parade.

116
00:06:14,207 --> 00:06:17,460
So call the CIA, tell them we want to
assassinate the president.

117
00:06:17,668 --> 00:06:19,295
We'll be home for <i>Wheel of Fortune.</i>

118
00:06:19,504 --> 00:06:21,547
BRITTA:
Who are we kidding? That'll never work.

119
00:06:21,756 --> 00:06:24,634
We got Britta'd. Yes, I use it too.

120
00:06:24,842 --> 00:06:27,845
I don't want anybody here
blaming themselves for this.

121
00:06:28,054 --> 00:06:29,639
I want everyone blaming Frankie.

122
00:06:29,847 --> 00:06:32,558
ANNIE: What? Dean. That's stupid.
-She's the reason we are here.

123
00:06:32,767 --> 00:06:36,521
This is what happens when you
make decisions outside the moment.

124
00:06:36,729 --> 00:06:40,566
Whatever moment you were in
the day you bought a gigantic hand,

125
00:06:40,775 --> 00:06:43,903
I am proud to
remain outside until I die.

126
00:06:44,112 --> 00:06:47,990
You will, baby.
And this is where logic gets you.

127
00:06:48,199 --> 00:06:52,703
Stuck in a rocky mountain pass at sundown,
gradually freezing to death.

128
00:06:52,912 --> 00:06:55,540
And forced to decide,
in the backs of our heads,

129
00:06:55,748 --> 00:06:58,084
just in case, who we'd eat first.
Annie, right?

130
00:06:58,292 --> 00:07:00,211
-What?
-Not a judgment. It's biology.

131
00:07:00,419 --> 00:07:02,171
-What?
JEFF: Craig.

132
00:07:02,380 --> 00:07:05,925
The hand currently crushing our lives
is not about being in the moment.

133
00:07:06,134 --> 00:07:08,928
You bought something we can't return
with money we don't have.

134
00:07:09,011 --> 00:07:12,056
Nobody knows why.
Your latest idea is to put it on the quad

135
00:07:12,265 --> 00:07:14,892
with a plaque that says,
"Give a hand to your brain."

136
00:07:15,101 --> 00:07:18,521
"Give your brain a hand."
You're making it sound stupid on purpose.

137
00:07:18,604 --> 00:07:21,107
It's over, Craig.
You are lucky to have Frankie.

138
00:07:21,315 --> 00:07:23,985
You're lucky she was able to
find some weirdo-- Excuse me.

139
00:07:24,193 --> 00:07:27,613
Bigger weirdo on eBay
willing to pay cash for it.

140
00:07:27,822 --> 00:07:31,033
This is a lot of narrative pipe.
Maybe we didn't need a flashback.

141
00:07:31,117 --> 00:07:34,203
Abed, is this a show? I thought you said
you knew it wasn't a TV show.

142
00:07:35,288 --> 00:07:37,790
Season two, you mean? Don't know.
I can change my mind.

143
00:07:37,915 --> 00:07:41,544
Can I ask that it not be a show about
you saying it's a show? Because dumb.

144
00:07:43,588 --> 00:07:45,256
-You're dumb.
-Go in the back.

145
00:07:45,465 --> 00:07:46,841
Go. Sit by yourself.

146
00:07:47,049 --> 00:07:49,677
PELTON: What are you doing?
ANNIE: Jeff, what is wrong with you?

147
00:07:49,886 --> 00:07:51,554
JEFF:
I'm sick of it. It's a show.

148
00:07:51,762 --> 00:07:55,933
It's not a show. It's your show. My show.
A good show. A bad show. I am sick of it.

149
00:07:56,142 --> 00:07:58,227
I don't want to hear
the word "show" again.

150
00:07:58,436 --> 00:08:01,022
Show, show, show. Is it a show?
Show, show, show.

151
00:08:01,230 --> 00:08:03,399
So now it's a show about this?

152
00:08:03,816 --> 00:08:05,818
You're right.
That's worse. Abed, come back.

153
00:08:06,027 --> 00:08:08,112
PELTON: Abed, come back.
-I'm not sorry.

154
00:08:08,321 --> 00:08:11,491
-It's not good to be back.
-What the hell was that?

155
00:08:11,908 --> 00:08:13,493
The battery is dead.

156
00:08:13,701 --> 00:08:16,454
-Flooded?
-Winger, so help me God...

157
00:08:16,662 --> 00:08:19,123
The RV has two batteries,
a primary and a--

158
00:08:19,332 --> 00:08:20,750
JEFF:
Secondary.

159
00:08:23,211 --> 00:08:25,838
We overloaded the electrical system
and killed the engine battery.

160
00:08:26,047 --> 00:08:28,925
So now the secondary battery
has three or four hours of juice--

161
00:08:29,008 --> 00:08:31,219
Charge. Juice charge.

162
00:08:32,929 --> 00:08:35,806
And we have a choice to make.
And Jeff can explain that choice.

163
00:08:36,015 --> 00:08:37,058
Oh, it's your RV.

164
00:08:37,266 --> 00:08:38,851
This was my show. You didn't care.

165
00:08:39,060 --> 00:08:40,561
Abed, we're all on your side.

166
00:08:40,770 --> 00:08:43,898
So if you're also on your side, it's petty.

167
00:08:44,357 --> 00:08:48,277
We could wait for a couple hours
and hope the engine battery resets itself.

168
00:08:48,486 --> 00:08:50,530
If it doesn't,
we're spending the night here.

169
00:08:50,738 --> 00:08:53,157
At least we have the secondary battery
to keep us warm.

170
00:08:53,241 --> 00:08:56,619
No. We're not spending the night here.
What's the second option?

171
00:08:56,827 --> 00:08:59,664
Which I am nicknaming "lil course of action."

172
00:08:59,872 --> 00:09:03,626
I rewire the secondary battery
to the engine and hope it can start it.

173
00:09:03,834 --> 00:09:07,255
If it doesn't, we're spending
a very cold night with two dead batteries.

174
00:09:07,463 --> 00:09:09,674
Okay, let's switch the batteries.
Good democracy.

175
00:09:09,757 --> 00:09:12,343
Are we sure the secondary battery won't die too?

176
00:09:12,426 --> 00:09:14,095
-Ha.
-It's a possibility.

177
00:09:14,178 --> 00:09:15,263
It exists.

178
00:09:15,429 --> 00:09:19,225
But I'm pretty confident because the
secondary battery only powers the cabin.

179
00:09:19,433 --> 00:09:20,810
And we've kept the lights off.

180
00:09:21,018 --> 00:09:25,064
And it goes without saying that we've
all learned to stop charging our phones.

181
00:09:29,860 --> 00:09:31,862
Why are you looking at each other like that?

182
00:09:32,071 --> 00:09:34,699
And where are each of your phones now?

183
00:09:39,245 --> 00:09:41,831
You know, I'm starting to suspect the unthinkable.

184
00:09:42,039 --> 00:09:44,625
Namely, that in spite of all we've experienced,

185
00:09:44,834 --> 00:09:48,921
there's a cartoonish, vampiric orgy
of personal devices somewhere in the RV,

186
00:09:49,130 --> 00:09:51,340
sucking away our remaining battery.

187
00:09:51,549 --> 00:09:56,137
I draw limited comfort from the fact
that nobody's running to unplug anything.

188
00:09:56,512 --> 00:09:58,514
But you know what...

189
00:09:59,140 --> 00:10:00,725
say nothing.

190
00:10:01,100 --> 00:10:02,893
I'll just...

191
00:10:03,686 --> 00:10:06,522
turn the light switch to the "on" position.

192
00:10:15,364 --> 00:10:17,992
[♪♪♪]

193
00:10:20,661 --> 00:10:22,663
There is a bright side to this.

194
00:10:22,872 --> 00:10:26,959
Most conventional weapons
don't require electricity.

195
00:10:27,877 --> 00:10:30,671
Are you going to eat me first?

196
00:10:34,050 --> 00:10:36,052
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]

197
00:10:38,137 --> 00:10:40,181
Hear those crickets?

198
00:10:40,723 --> 00:10:44,185
This would be a challenging place
to practice your stand-up act.

199
00:10:45,895 --> 00:10:49,231
So I rented <i>Hotel Rwanda</i> the other night.
Let me just say:

200
00:10:49,440 --> 00:10:51,609
Not a date movie.

201
00:10:53,944 --> 00:10:59,408
What would Arnold Schwarzenegger
sound like if he was bit by Dracula?

202
00:11:01,243 --> 00:11:02,787
All in favor?

203
00:11:02,995 --> 00:11:06,332
That solves the matter of the giant hand.
If there's no other business--

204
00:11:06,540 --> 00:11:09,418
I'd like to re-state the importance
of telling this story with flashbacks.

205
00:11:09,627 --> 00:11:10,961
What do you mean by re-state?

206
00:11:11,170 --> 00:11:13,464
Oh, my God. I fell for it. Meeting adjourned.

207
00:11:17,051 --> 00:11:21,222
Why do we call them "elbows"?
Why not "arm knees"?

208
00:11:22,390 --> 00:11:24,767
Man, I am dying up here.
Heh-heh-heh.

209
00:11:25,101 --> 00:11:29,605
I'm scaling the blanket rations inversely
to the wattage of each person's phone.

210
00:11:29,772 --> 00:11:32,066
That way, the person who killed us the most

211
00:11:32,233 --> 00:11:34,777
will die the soonest, which feels fair.

212
00:11:35,027 --> 00:11:36,779
Right, Britta?

213
00:11:40,366 --> 00:11:43,744
I can't go all night being this angry.

214
00:11:44,203 --> 00:11:46,330
Heart attacks run in my family,

215
00:11:46,539 --> 00:11:48,541
and you people aren't worth it!

216
00:11:48,916 --> 00:11:50,709
-I'm sorry.
BRITTA: It's okay.

217
00:11:50,918 --> 00:11:54,213
I caused the situation
by not topping off the tank.

218
00:11:54,422 --> 00:11:58,467
And that vinyl accordion partition
is a totem of distrust.

219
00:11:58,676 --> 00:12:00,010
I'm sorry for that too.

220
00:12:00,219 --> 00:12:02,388
Elroy, that's big of you.

221
00:12:02,596 --> 00:12:05,975
For our part, we're sorry that charging
our perfectly normal cell phones

222
00:12:06,058 --> 00:12:08,102
destroyed your weirdly fragile RV.

223
00:12:09,145 --> 00:12:11,063
Okay, I'm sorry about that apology.

224
00:12:11,272 --> 00:12:13,399
I'll try to be a better house guest.

225
00:12:13,482 --> 00:12:15,234
[SCREECHING]

226
00:12:17,278 --> 00:12:20,406
Sorry I was unavailable.
I was trying to cut to three weeks earlier.

227
00:12:20,573 --> 00:12:24,285
-It really feels like we needed that.
BRITTA: I have to apologize as well.

228
00:12:24,493 --> 00:12:28,539
Perhaps you recall when it seemed as though
we drove through a skunk patch.

229
00:12:28,747 --> 00:12:30,666
-You were getting high.
-Smoking pot.

230
00:12:30,875 --> 00:12:32,751
ELROY: Getting stoned.
-Oh, okay.

231
00:12:32,960 --> 00:12:35,754
I remember thinking,
"I really pulled that one off."

232
00:12:35,963 --> 00:12:37,214
ANNIE:
Because you were high.

233
00:12:37,423 --> 00:12:39,467
You also thought that
we were speeding

234
00:12:39,633 --> 00:12:41,760
because you
"kept seeing the same bird."

235
00:12:42,553 --> 00:12:44,013
Unh!

236
00:12:45,639 --> 00:12:46,724
Unh!

237
00:12:47,766 --> 00:12:48,809
All in favor?

238
00:12:49,560 --> 00:12:52,730
That solves the matter of the giant hand.
If there's no other business--

239
00:12:52,938 --> 00:12:55,649
Let me explain the need for a flashback here.
Don't interrupt.

240
00:12:55,733 --> 00:12:58,277
One quick thing,
then you can talk about flashbacks forever.

241
00:12:58,486 --> 00:12:59,778
Meeting adjourned.

242
00:12:59,987 --> 00:13:02,573
Abed, when they cut to
three weeks earlier on TV,

243
00:13:02,781 --> 00:13:05,075
-they're not traveling in time, dip-ass.
-Jeff.

244
00:13:05,367 --> 00:13:07,369
ANNIE:
Okay, my apology now.

245
00:13:07,578 --> 00:13:10,581
I've had some time to think about it,
and I've decided...

246
00:13:10,664 --> 00:13:14,251
I'm sorry for not asking people what they wanted
before buying snacks for the trip.

247
00:13:14,460 --> 00:13:16,045
-Wow, really?
-That's great.

248
00:13:16,253 --> 00:13:19,423
What? Think about it.
It's the worst thing I've done on this trip.

249
00:13:19,632 --> 00:13:22,760
-I've been nailing it.
-She has.

250
00:13:22,843 --> 00:13:24,011
You have.

251
00:13:24,220 --> 00:13:25,930
I haven't been.

252
00:13:26,138 --> 00:13:29,975
I shouldn't be yelling at the dean
in front of any of you. It's unprofessional.

253
00:13:30,184 --> 00:13:33,437
Oh, you're all right, Frankie.
We got no complaints.

254
00:13:37,107 --> 00:13:38,651
[PELTON SIGHS]

255
00:13:42,321 --> 00:13:45,950
I forgive all of you. Heh-heh-heh.

256
00:13:51,705 --> 00:13:52,915
What?

257
00:13:54,291 --> 00:13:56,585
That solves the giant hand.
If there's no other business--

258
00:13:56,669 --> 00:13:59,421
In a normal road-trip story,
first act would end with us deciding to go.

259
00:13:59,505 --> 00:14:02,675
Second act would be the trip ending with disaster,
third act would be us returning.

260
00:14:02,758 --> 00:14:04,885
Problem is, we decided
to take this trip weeks from now.

261
00:14:04,969 --> 00:14:07,012
The story starts with us already on the road.

262
00:14:07,221 --> 00:14:09,557
So the end of act one
will have to be the disaster.

263
00:14:09,765 --> 00:14:11,767
So something worse has to happen in act two.

264
00:14:11,976 --> 00:14:14,353
Unless we decide now
that act one is a flashback,

265
00:14:14,562 --> 00:14:17,231
so the beginning of the story
is now instead of then.

266
00:14:24,238 --> 00:14:25,948
You forgive us?

267
00:14:26,282 --> 00:14:27,491
Absolutely.

268
00:14:27,867 --> 00:14:29,827
You turd.

269
00:14:30,035 --> 00:14:31,829
-I beg your pardon?
-Guys.

270
00:14:32,037 --> 00:14:34,582
You have no sense of accountability.
You're a child.

271
00:14:34,748 --> 00:14:37,751
If I'm a child, you're a child abuser.
No. Not cool, Annie.

272
00:14:37,960 --> 00:14:43,173
You never said, "Leave my hand where it is.
I like it there. I demand it stay."

273
00:14:43,382 --> 00:14:45,259
Because everyone complained about it.

274
00:14:45,467 --> 00:14:48,637
Where's that commitment
when we're admitting we did stuff wrong?

275
00:14:48,846 --> 00:14:51,390
Okay, I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
I'm a bad dean. Okay?

276
00:14:51,599 --> 00:14:53,851
That's what you always do.
Not a real apology.

277
00:14:54,059 --> 00:14:56,854
-Jeff?
-Shut up. Go flashback and cut to stuff.

278
00:14:57,062 --> 00:14:59,148
Say you're sorry for buying a giant hand

279
00:14:59,356 --> 00:15:02,818
and letting it sit around until we dealt with it.
Say it without crying.

280
00:15:03,027 --> 00:15:06,447
No. I'm an adult.
And you can't make me not cry.

281
00:15:06,655 --> 00:15:09,950
You're all a bunch of bullies,
and I will say I'm sorry however I want.

282
00:15:10,159 --> 00:15:12,453
And by the way, I'm not sorry!

283
00:15:12,661 --> 00:15:15,789
It's my giant hand and I love it!

284
00:15:15,998 --> 00:15:17,958
We're not selling it!

285
00:15:18,709 --> 00:15:20,377
This is like crate-training a puppy.

286
00:15:20,586 --> 00:15:23,464
Suppress every instinct
to let him sleep in bed with us.

287
00:15:24,048 --> 00:15:25,758
Cold.

288
00:15:26,258 --> 00:15:29,094
I mean in the RV.
I don't care how we treat the dean tonight.

289
00:15:31,722 --> 00:15:33,891
Abed, don't go after--

290
00:15:41,899 --> 00:15:44,818
Did they send you out here
to be mean to me too?

291
00:15:46,737 --> 00:15:47,821
-No.
-Good.

292
00:15:48,030 --> 00:15:51,575
Because I can't cry anymore
unless someone brings me a Pedialyte.

293
00:16:01,293 --> 00:16:02,795
Here.

294
00:16:04,088 --> 00:16:05,547
Here.

295
00:16:13,722 --> 00:16:14,932
Pretty comforting, huh?

296
00:16:15,140 --> 00:16:17,434
We could have put it
outside the Art Department.

297
00:16:17,643 --> 00:16:21,021
Or Biology. Or Woodworking,
if we removed one of the fingers.

298
00:16:21,230 --> 00:16:23,607
You don't belong up here.
It's not right.

299
00:16:23,816 --> 00:16:28,320
You get it, don't you, Abed?
You know what's important about the hand.

300
00:16:28,529 --> 00:16:31,740
No. I know what's important about story.
We're overdue for a disaster.

301
00:16:31,949 --> 00:16:33,117
Great.

302
00:16:33,325 --> 00:16:36,745
Figures. The one person on my side
is the one playing people chess.

303
00:16:37,579 --> 00:16:38,664
[SCREAMS]

304
00:16:38,831 --> 00:16:41,709
-Don't move. Don't move.
-What the hell are we supposed to do?

305
00:16:41,917 --> 00:16:43,085
-Flashback with me.
-What?

306
00:16:43,293 --> 00:16:46,505
Trust me. I set a flashback three weeks earlier.
It's how this begins.

307
00:16:46,714 --> 00:16:48,549
Close your eyes and concentrate.

308
00:16:48,757 --> 00:16:50,175
[PELTON GRUNTING]

309
00:16:50,384 --> 00:16:51,927
[ABED GRUNTING]

310
00:16:53,095 --> 00:16:56,223
FRANKIE: That solves the matter
of the giant hand. If there's no other business--

311
00:16:56,306 --> 00:16:57,891
-There's business.
ABED: There's business.

312
00:16:58,058 --> 00:17:01,895
When we tie the hand to the roof,
we'd like you to use extra-thick straps.

313
00:17:01,979 --> 00:17:04,106
-Extra-thick.
-Extra-thick straps.

314
00:17:04,314 --> 00:17:07,526
-Reinforced.
-All right. Meeting adjourned. Aah!

315
00:17:08,485 --> 00:17:10,279
BOTH:
♪ Extra-thick straps ♪

316
00:17:10,487 --> 00:17:12,197
♪ Extra-thick straps ♪

317
00:17:12,406 --> 00:17:14,074
♪ Extra-thick straps ♪

318
00:17:14,283 --> 00:17:15,951
♪ Extra-thick straps ♪♪

319
00:17:16,160 --> 00:17:18,746
-There, that should do it.
-What should do it?

320
00:17:18,954 --> 00:17:22,207
-We ensured the straps were extra-thick.
-No, it didn't happen!

321
00:17:22,416 --> 00:17:23,959
It didn't?

322
00:17:24,043 --> 00:17:25,836
[RUMBLING AND PELTON SCREAMS]

323
00:17:26,003 --> 00:17:27,087
FRANKIE:
What?

324
00:17:27,254 --> 00:17:28,338
[THUDDING]

325
00:17:28,505 --> 00:17:30,299
Did something just fall off the roof?

326
00:17:30,507 --> 00:17:32,509
That's a really stupid question, Annie.

327
00:17:32,718 --> 00:17:35,554
Obviously something fell off the roof.
The question is what?

328
00:17:35,763 --> 00:17:37,723
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

329
00:17:43,854 --> 00:17:45,564
Abed, where's the dean?

330
00:17:46,648 --> 00:17:47,858
Oh, damn. Come on.

331
00:17:49,568 --> 00:17:50,694
[ALL GRUNTING]

332
00:17:50,861 --> 00:17:52,446
JEFF:
Okay, one, two, three.

333
00:17:52,654 --> 00:17:54,406
Carefully. Carefully.

334
00:17:54,615 --> 00:17:57,117
How do you lift a giant hand
off a person haphazardly?

335
00:17:57,326 --> 00:17:58,786
-You know what, Annie--
-No!

336
00:17:58,994 --> 00:18:02,206
-Dean, hang on.
-Dean, we're so sorry. We love you.

337
00:18:05,584 --> 00:18:07,127
-Screw you!
BRITTA: What?

338
00:18:07,336 --> 00:18:11,215
ELROY: Hey, that's my house.
-We are not sorry. We hate you!

339
00:18:11,423 --> 00:18:14,134
-Are we gonna freeze to death?
-I call the hand.

340
00:18:15,594 --> 00:18:18,430
The fiberglass will preserve body heat.

341
00:18:18,639 --> 00:18:20,474
[GRUNTING]

342
00:18:21,517 --> 00:18:23,936
What's wrong with me that that's hot?

343
00:18:27,773 --> 00:18:30,484
Dean, these temperatures
are lowering our immune systems

344
00:18:30,692 --> 00:18:34,279
in a world that's swarming
with weird people's unvaccinated toddlers.

345
00:18:34,488 --> 00:18:35,572
PELTON:
Deal with it.

346
00:18:35,781 --> 00:18:38,700
ELROY: I'll go to the other side
to see if he's locked that door too.

347
00:18:39,076 --> 00:18:41,703
It probably undercuts my goals
to announce them out loud.

348
00:18:41,912 --> 00:18:46,250
But I'm a verbal thinker.
I'm not even sure I have an idea until I say it.

349
00:18:47,835 --> 00:18:50,546
They should make hiking boots
with a compass in the toe.

350
00:18:50,754 --> 00:18:52,131
ALL:
Go.

351
00:18:52,798 --> 00:18:56,844
Dean? We're sorry and we love you?

352
00:18:57,052 --> 00:18:59,596
PELTON:
Nice uncontrollable question mark, Britta.

353
00:18:59,805 --> 00:19:01,098
You can't even fake it?

354
00:19:01,306 --> 00:19:04,059
Dean, we're sorry and we love you.

355
00:19:04,268 --> 00:19:05,727
PELTON:
Super realistic, Annie.

356
00:19:05,936 --> 00:19:08,063
You're a real sociopath.

357
00:19:08,272 --> 00:19:10,858
I saw all your true colors
when the chips were down.

358
00:19:11,024 --> 00:19:14,695
Abed's the only human among you,
and I think we all know how ironic that is.

359
00:19:14,903 --> 00:19:16,613
-No offense, Abed.
-None possible.

360
00:19:16,822 --> 00:19:17,948
Abed.

361
00:19:18,157 --> 00:19:20,325
You bonded with him. Talk to him.

362
00:19:20,534 --> 00:19:23,495
You're alone in the end zone.
This ball is yours or nobody's.

363
00:19:23,704 --> 00:19:25,873
I appreciate your appeal
to my well-known passion

364
00:19:26,039 --> 00:19:27,457
for athletics and sarcasm.

365
00:19:27,624 --> 00:19:29,418
We didn't bond, I almost killed him.

366
00:19:29,626 --> 00:19:31,962
My obsession with
contrived flashback technique

367
00:19:32,171 --> 00:19:34,548
has kept me from being invested
in any of this story.

368
00:19:34,715 --> 00:19:35,757
What was it, even?

369
00:19:35,966 --> 00:19:38,552
Bunch of people in an RV?
I had to Christopher Nolan it?

370
00:19:38,760 --> 00:19:39,803
Well, there you go.

371
00:19:40,012 --> 00:19:41,471
Now you can forget all about

372
00:19:41,680 --> 00:19:44,558
stupid "three weeks earlier" flashbacks
and be a hero.

373
00:19:44,766 --> 00:19:46,977
By joining us here, in the moment.

374
00:19:47,186 --> 00:19:49,104
And talking to the dean like a human.

375
00:19:49,646 --> 00:19:51,190
-That's my arc.
-That's your arc.

376
00:19:52,983 --> 00:19:54,860
Okay. Here we go.

377
00:19:55,986 --> 00:19:57,112
[GRUNTING]

378
00:19:57,905 --> 00:20:01,325
-If there's no other business--
-I'd like to propose a heavy use of flashback.

379
00:20:01,533 --> 00:20:03,744
-No, Abed. Don't do it.
-Thanks, Abed.

380
00:20:03,911 --> 00:20:06,038
Stop! Get your head out of your ass.

381
00:20:06,205 --> 00:20:09,458
I can't. I'm over-saturated with the gimmick.
Don't know what's real.

382
00:20:09,708 --> 00:20:13,420
-You have to be lying. You enjoy this.
-Stop it. What has gotten into you?

383
00:20:13,629 --> 00:20:15,672
Why are you shocked
that he's alienated?

384
00:20:15,881 --> 00:20:18,217
You get him to do something normal
without abuse.

385
00:20:18,800 --> 00:20:19,968
Abed, listen.

386
00:20:20,177 --> 00:20:22,095
This is a flashback, remember?

387
00:20:22,304 --> 00:20:24,640
The real story is happening in the future.

388
00:20:24,848 --> 00:20:27,935
You actually flashed back to now to help us.

389
00:20:29,269 --> 00:20:30,812
Okay, that was pretty good.

390
00:20:35,651 --> 00:20:39,446
So sad what happened here,
all those centons ago.

391
00:20:39,655 --> 00:20:41,782
So sad. So preventable.

392
00:20:41,990 --> 00:20:45,786
Space Elder Abed, can you reach backward
with your mind and save our species?

393
00:20:46,161 --> 00:20:47,829
I can.

394
00:20:47,955 --> 00:20:50,374
I'm Space Elder Britta.

395
00:20:55,963 --> 00:20:57,464
What are you guys talking about?

396
00:21:05,597 --> 00:21:08,267
I'm here now, child.
All will be made right.

397
00:21:10,978 --> 00:21:12,646
-Dean.
PELTON: Abed.

398
00:21:12,854 --> 00:21:15,065
ABED: I have discovered the meaning
of the giant hand.

399
00:21:15,148 --> 00:21:16,108
[♪♪♪]

400
00:21:16,191 --> 00:21:19,611
A hand has two functions,
to grip and to release.

401
00:21:19,820 --> 00:21:23,115
But without both of these powers,
it is useless.

402
00:21:23,323 --> 00:21:26,076
Like newborn infants,
we grab what comes near us,

403
00:21:26,285 --> 00:21:28,328
hoping to control it, taste it,

404
00:21:28,537 --> 00:21:31,081
jam it into another child's eye.

405
00:21:31,415 --> 00:21:34,167
But the time we spend
in control of our world...

406
00:21:35,168 --> 00:21:37,045
is the time we spend
letting go of others.

407
00:21:38,005 --> 00:21:39,840
Ideas, stories, pride,

408
00:21:40,048 --> 00:21:43,093
girls in soft sweaters, video games,
buttered noodles...

409
00:21:43,302 --> 00:21:47,597
Grip one for too long and you lose
so much that you've never held.

410
00:21:50,851 --> 00:21:54,563
This giant hand was sent
to all of us as an invitation,

411
00:21:54,771 --> 00:21:58,066
to increase our mastery
over the power to hold on.

412
00:21:59,192 --> 00:22:00,902
And let go.

413
00:22:01,278 --> 00:22:03,905
[♪♪♪]

414
00:22:08,952 --> 00:22:10,537
Sorry.

415
00:22:11,079 --> 00:22:13,290
ANNIE: Dean.
FRANKIE: Heh-heh-heh.

416
00:22:13,457 --> 00:22:15,292
JEFF: Dummy.
ANNIE: I kind of hate you.

417
00:22:16,418 --> 00:22:20,839
[♪♪♪]

418
00:22:26,553 --> 00:22:28,847
The doors were locked
on that side too.

419
00:22:29,389 --> 00:22:30,640
Took you long enough.

420
00:22:31,016 --> 00:22:33,477
I'd be lying if I said I didn't poop.

421
00:22:34,561 --> 00:22:35,979
Could you lie, then?

422
00:22:36,188 --> 00:22:37,564
Sure I can.

423
00:22:37,773 --> 00:22:40,984
Sure I can. Heh-heh-heh.

424
00:22:41,568 --> 00:22:42,986
I slapped you, man.

425
00:22:45,989 --> 00:22:47,032
[♪♪♪]

426
00:22:47,240 --> 00:22:50,077
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

427
00:22:56,374 --> 00:22:57,667
Where were you?

428
00:22:57,876 --> 00:23:01,213
The reason why
I'm covered in feathers is because--

429
00:23:01,421 --> 00:23:04,466
{\an8}[♪♪♪]

430
00:23:12,974 --> 00:23:17,104
Hi, this is Blake, the gentleman
to whom you are selling the giant hand.

431
00:23:17,312 --> 00:23:21,858
I am calling to confirm
that you have the correct address.

432
00:23:22,067 --> 00:23:24,319
We live at the end of
a long driveway,

433
00:23:24,528 --> 00:23:28,281
which often gets
confused with a road.

434
00:23:28,490 --> 00:23:32,953
Anyway, it's been many hours
since our scheduled appointment time.

435
00:23:33,161 --> 00:23:36,373
Again, it's Blake with a "B."

436
00:23:36,581 --> 00:23:39,584
The purchaser of the giant hand.

437
00:23:39,793 --> 00:23:41,336
Bye.

438
00:23:44,005 --> 00:23:45,465
[SIGHS]

439
00:23:57,936 --> 00:24:00,939
-They're not coming?
-I don't know, Karen. I left a message.

440
00:24:01,148 --> 00:24:05,068
-What are you gonna do with--?
-With the giant watch?

441
00:24:05,277 --> 00:24:08,113
I don't know. I don't plan for failure.

442
00:24:08,321 --> 00:24:10,031
Have you tried planning for success?

443
00:24:10,240 --> 00:24:13,451
Does everything you do
to this family have--?

444
00:24:13,869 --> 00:24:16,288
No, finish your thought.

445
00:24:16,496 --> 00:24:17,664
Finish your thought.

446
00:24:17,873 --> 00:24:21,543
Does everything have to do
with me purchasing

447
00:24:21,751 --> 00:24:24,129
oversized items on the Internet?

448
00:24:24,337 --> 00:24:29,092
But that's not what this is about, is it?
It's not about a giant hand or watch--

449
00:24:29,301 --> 00:24:32,679
-Please don’t.
-It's about a normal-sized son

450
00:24:32,888 --> 00:24:34,598
who disappeared.

451
00:24:34,806 --> 00:24:36,850
And it's all my fault,

452
00:24:37,058 --> 00:24:41,188
because I gave him a giant kite! Argh!

453
00:24:41,354 --> 00:24:44,441
Yes! How could you not make that connection?

454
00:24:44,649 --> 00:24:48,820
Why do you continue to buy
giant-sized versions of everyday objects,

455
00:24:49,029 --> 00:24:51,156
when they are the reason our son is dead?

456
00:24:51,364 --> 00:24:53,491
Disappeared! Disappeared!

457
00:24:53,700 --> 00:24:57,662
They never found his body on the ground,
which proves he's still up there waiting.

458
00:24:57,871 --> 00:25:00,415
He's waiting for a better daddy

459
00:25:00,624 --> 00:25:03,251
with a bigger hand.

460
00:25:05,462 --> 00:25:06,546
Oh.

461
00:25:08,882 --> 00:25:10,634
Really?

462
00:25:11,301 --> 00:25:13,637
So then why the watch?

463
00:25:13,845 --> 00:25:15,555
I thought it would look really cool.

464
00:25:16,056 --> 00:25:18,099
I'm gonna walk the dog,

465
00:25:18,308 --> 00:25:20,977
and eventually leave you.

466
00:25:21,186 --> 00:25:24,481
I'll put the watch in the garage.

467
00:25:25,732 --> 00:25:27,817
And probably stop showering.

